{
  "answer": "**Viṣṇu Smṛti (also known as Vishnu Smriti) Chapter 2 does not specifically prescribe anything for a king who has just risen from sleep.**[^1]\n\nThe chapter focuses instead on the four *varṇas* (Brāhmaṇa, Kṣatriya, Vaiśya, and Śūdra), their duties (*dharma*)—such as teaching for Brāhmaṇas, arms practice for Kṣatriyas, cattle-tending for Vaiśyas, and service for Śūdras—their livelihoods, allowances in times of distress, and a list of common virtues like forbearance, truthfulness, and non-violence.[^1] Kings (*rājan*) are not mentioned, nor is any daily routine involving sleep or waking.\n\nThe *Viṣṇu Smṛti* has 100 chapters in this corpus, and topics like royal duties may appear elsewhere (e.g., later chapters on governance), but Chapter 2 covers only the general *varṇa* framework above.[^2]\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, Chapter 2 (translation), [chapter](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/02/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Chapters overview for *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, via corpus metadata.",
